<p>the fca found that 6 million loyal insurance customers were paying £1.2 billion more than they should. not because their risk profile changed. not because they made a claim. because they stayed.</p>

<p>that's the loyalty penalty: the price of doing nothing.</p>

<p>in 2022, the fca banned the worst of it — insurers can no longer offer new customers a price they won't offer existing ones. but the data shows it's still happening. car insurance renewal premiums rose an average of £82 in 2024 alone, and 47% of drivers didn't check before accepting.</p>

<h4>what changed with the fca rules</h4>

<p>the 2022 rules (ps21/5, if you like reading regulations) stopped insurers from what's called "price walking" — the practice of raising premiums incrementally each year for loyal customers. on paper, this means your renewal quote can't be higher than what a new customer would pay for the same policy.</p>

<p>in practice, the industry found ways around it. the baseline price went up for everyone. new customer discounts got smaller. the gap narrowed, but the penalty didn't disappear.</p>

<h4>what this means for you</h4>

<p>the fca fix was necessary but not sufficient. it addressed the most visible symptom — the annual price hike — but not the underlying dynamic: people don't check their renewal because checking feels like work. and when they don't check, they overpay.</p>

<p>perch. doesn't change the insurance industry. it changes your relationship to it. by surfacing exactly what's changing and when, it removes the friction from checking — and that's where the real savings are.</p>

